normal" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2222em;">V</span></span></span></span></sp=
an>) and current (<span class=3D"math-inline" data-math=3D"I" data-index-in=
-node=3D"78"><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=
=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.683=
3em;"></span><span class=3D"mord mathnormal" style=3D"margin-right: 0.0785e=
m;">I</span></span></span></span></span>). If you draw too much current, th=
e voltage drops; if the voltage is too high, the current drops.</p><p data-=
path-to-node=3D"5">There is one specific point where the product of the two=
=E2=80=94the wattage (<span class=3D"math-inline" data-math=3D"P =3D V \tim=
es I" data-index-in-node=3D"70"><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-=
html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=
