><structured-content-container _ngcontent-ng-c2491911150=3D"" class=3D"mode=
l-response-text processing-state-visible ng-star-inserted" _nghost-ng-c1082=
903860=3D"" style=3D"height: auto;"><div _ngcontent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"container"><message-content _ngcontent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" _nghost-ng=
-c1716333038=3D"" id=3D"message-content-id-r_df550e437858c5ad" class=3D"ng-=
star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c1716333038=3D"" inline-copy-host=3D"" cl=
ass=3D"markdown markdown-main-panel enable-updated-hr-color" id=3D"model-re=
sponse-message-contentr_df550e437858c5ad" aria-live=3D"off" aria-busy=3D"fa=
lse" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animation-fun=
ction: linear;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0">Since you are looking at a <b da=
ta-path-to-node=3D"0" data-index-in-node=3D"27">three-phase 240V/400V</b> h=
ybrid system, phase balancing is the "secret sauce" that keeps your utility=
 meter from spinning even when your solar production and house loads don't =
match up.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"1">In a perfect world, every appliance=
 in your house would pull exactly the same amount of power from Phase L1, L=
2, and L3. In reality, your oven is on L1, your toaster is on L2, and your =
PC is on L3.</p><hr data-path-to-node=3D"2"><h2 data-path-to-node=3D"3">1. =
The "Phase Imbalance" Problem</h2><p data-path-to-node=3D"4">Imagine it=E2=
=80=99s a sunny day. Your AC microinverters are humming along, but they are=
 distributed across all three phases.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"5"><li><p=
 data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-index-in-n=
ode=3D"0">Solar Production:</b> 2kW on L1, 2kW on L2, 2kW on L3 (<b data-pa=
th-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"51">6kW Total</b>).</p></li><li>=
<p data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in=
-node=3D"0">House Load:</b> 5kW on L1 (Oven), 0.5kW on L2, 0.5kW on L3 (<b =
data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"56">6kW Total</b>).</p></=
li></ul><p data-path-to-node=3D"6">Even though your total production matche=
s your total load, <b data-path-to-node=3D"6" data-index-in-node=3D"59">L1 =
is short by 3kW</b>, while <b data-path-to-node=3D"6" data-index-in-node=3D=
"85">L2 and L3 have a 1.5kW surplus</b> each.</p><hr data-path-to-node=3D"7=
"><h2 data-path-to-node=3D"8">2. How the Hybrid Inverter Fixes It (Net Mete=
ring)</h2><p data-path-to-node=3D"9">Modern hybrid inverters use a <b data-=
path-to-node=3D"9" data-index-in-node=3D"30">Smart Meter</b> (or CT Clamps)=
 at the point where your house connects to the grid. The inverter "watches"=
 the sum of all three phases.</p><ol start=3D"1" data-path-to-node=3D"10"><=
li><p data-path-to-node=3D"10,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10,0,0" data-ind=
ex-in-node=3D"0">The Calculation:</b> The inverter sees that L2 and L3 are =
pushing power <i data-path-to-node=3D"10,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"68">out=
</i> to the grid, while L1 is pulling power <i data-path-to-node=3D"10,0,0"=
 data-index-in-node=3D"111">in</i>.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"10,=
1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Compensat=
ion:</b> Through a process called <b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-inde=
x-in-node=3D"43">Vector Summation</b>, the inverter adjusts its battery out=
put. It will pull DC energy from the battery and "inject" it specifically i=
nto Phase L1 to zero out that 3kW deficit.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"10,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Go=
al:</b> The Smart Meter should read <b data-path-to-node=3D"10,2,0" data-in=
dex-in-node=3D"38">0.0 Watts</b> across the total of all three phases combi=
ned.</p></li></ol><hr data-path-to-node=3D"11"><h2 data-path-to-node=3D"12"=
>3. Physical vs. Financial Balancing</h2><p data-path-to-node=3D"13">Depend=
ing on where you live (like Germany or Australia), "balancing" happens in t=
wo ways:</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"14"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"14,0,0=
"><b data-path-to-node=3D"14,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Financial Balanc=
ing (Net Metering):</b> The utility meter just adds up <span class=3D"math-=
inline" data-math=3D"L1 + L2 + L3" data-index-in-node=3D"67"><span class=3D=
"katex"><span class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base=
"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.7667em; vertical-align: -0.0833e=
m;"></span><span class=3D"mord mathnormal">L</span><span class=3D"mord">1</=
span><span class=3D"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span><span =
class=3D"mbin">+</span><span class=3D"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2222=
em;"></span></span><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"heig=
ht: 0.7667em; vertical-align: -0.0833em;"></span><span class=3D"mord mathno=
rmal">L</span><span class=3D"mord">2</span><span class=3D"mspace" style=3D"=
margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span><span class=3D"mbin">+</span><span class=3D=
"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2222em;"></span></span><span class=3D"bas=
e"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class=3D"=
mord mathnormal">L</span><span class=3D"mord">3</span></span></span></span>=
</span>. If the sum is zero, you pay nothing. The inverter doesn't have to =
work as hard here because the "balancing" happens on the utility's bill.</p=
></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"14,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"14,1,0" d=
ata-index-in-node=3D"0">Physical Balancing (Zero Export):</b> If your utili=
ty <i data-path-to-node=3D"14,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"50">doesn't</i> al=
low export, the Hybrid Inverter must physically move energy between the pha=
ses (using the DC battery bus as a bridge) to ensure no single phase ever p=
ushes power back to the street.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"15"><=
h2 data-path-to-node=3D"16">4. The "Asymmetric" Capability</h2><p data-path=
-to-node=3D"17">When shopping for your hybrid inverter, look for the term <=
b data-path-to-node=3D"17" data-index-in-node=3D"58">"100% Unbalanced Load =
Capability."</b></p><p data-path-to-node=3D"18">Cheap three-phase inverters=
 can only output power equally (e.g., if it needs to give 3kW to L1, it's f=
orced to give 3kW to L2 and L3 as well). A "good" hybrid inverter is <b dat=
a-path-to-node=3D"18" data-index-in-node=3D"171">asymmetric</b>=E2=80=94it =
can put 100% of its power into a single phase if that=E2=80=99s where the t=
oaster is running, while keeping the other two phases at zero.</p><hr data-=
path-to-node=3D"19"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"20">Summary of your AC-Coupled=
 3-Phase Dream Setup:</h3><ol start=3D"1" data-path-to-node=3D"21"><li><p d=
ata-path-to-node=3D"21,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"21,0,0" data-index-in-n=
ode=3D"0">Microinverters:</b> Handle the MPPT and shading on the roof, outp=
utting AC.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"21,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=
=3D"21,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Hybrid Inverter:</b> Acts as the "Grid=
 Boss," using frequency shifting to manage the micros and using its battery=
 to "plug the holes" on whichever phase needs power.</p></li><li><p data-pa=
th-to-node=3D"21,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"21,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D=
"0">Smart Meter:</b> Sits at the front door of your electrical system, tell=
ing the inverter exactly how to balance the three phases to keep your bill =
at zero.</p></li></ol><p data-path-to-node=3D"22"><b data-path-to-node=3D"2=
2" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Since we've covered the physics and the balanci=
ng, would you like me to help you draft a "System Checklist" of technical s=
pecs you should look for when you start shopping for the actual hardware?</=
b></p></div></message-content><!----></div></structured-content-container><=
