_ngcontent-ng-c2491911150=3D"" class=3D"cdk-visually-hidden ng-star-inserte=
d"> Gemini said </h2><!----><!----><structured-content-container _ngcontent=
-ng-c2491911150=3D"" class=3D"model-response-text processing-state-visible =
ng-star-inserted" _nghost-ng-c1082903860=3D"" style=3D"height: auto;"><div =
_ngcontent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" class=3D"container"><message-content _ngcont=
ent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" _nghost-ng-c1716333038=3D"" id=3D"message-content-i=
d-r_7866648549bde997" class=3D"ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c171633=
3038=3D"" inline-copy-host=3D"" class=3D"markdown markdown-main-panel enabl=
e-updated-hr-color" id=3D"model-response-message-contentr_7866648549bde997"=
 aria-live=3D"off" aria-busy=3D"false" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-dur=
ation: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0=
">In the strict engineering sense, you have stumbled upon a naming quirk in=
 the industry. While people often use "Hybrid" as a catch-all term, there i=
s a more precise name for the device you are describing.</p><h3 data-path-t=
o-node=3D"1">1. The Correct Term: "Battery Inverter" or "AC-Coupled Inverte=
r"</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"2">If a device converts AC to DC to charge a=
 battery, and DC to AC to discharge it, but has <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" =
data-index-in-node=3D"89">no</b> DC solar inputs (MPPTs), it is technically=
 a <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"137">Battery Inverter</=
b> (or sometimes an <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"171">O=
ff-Grid Inverter/Charger</b>).</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"3"><li><p data-p=
ath-to-node=3D"3,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"=
0">Hybrid Inverter:</b> A "hybrid" of a Solar Inverter and a Battery Invert=
er. It has DC inputs for panels <i data-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0" data-index-i=
n-node=3D"100">and</i> a connection for batteries.</p></li><li><p data-path=
-to-node=3D"3,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"3,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">=
Battery Inverter:</b> Only handles the battery. It "couples" with your sola=
r system via the AC wiring.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"4"><h3 da=
ta-path-to-node=3D"5">2. Why the names get mixed up</h3><p data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"6">In 2026, the lines are blurring because of how these units are mark=
eted:</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"7"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0"><b =
data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Victron Energy:</b> Th=
ey call their famous "MultiPlus" units <b data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data-=
index-in-node=3D"57">Inverter/Chargers</b>. They are the king of AC-couplin=
g, but technically not "hybrids" because they don't have built-in solar MPP=
Ts (you buy those separately).</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0"><=
b data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Tesla Powerwall:</b>=
 This is technically an <b data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=
=3D"40">AC-Coupled Battery System</b>. It has a battery inverter hidden ins=
ide the casing, but no solar string inputs.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"7,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"7,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The "Hy=
brid" shortcut:</b> Many installers call anything that manages a battery a =
"Hybrid" because it's easier to explain to customers that the system "hybri=
dizes" solar and storage.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"8"><h3 data=
-path-to-node=3D"9">3. Which one should you shop for?</h3><p data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"10">Since you want an AC-coupled system with microinverters, you are=
 specifically looking for a <b data-path-to-node=3D"10" data-index-in-node=
=3D"92">3-Phase Battery Inverter with Grid-Forming capabilities</b>.</p><p =
data-path-to-node=3D"11">If you mistakenly buy a "Hybrid Inverter," you are=
 paying for DC solar electronics (MPPTs) inside the box that you aren't goi=
ng to use. However, many modern 3-phase hybrids are now priced so competiti=
vely that people buy them even if they only intend to use the AC-coupling f=
eature.</p><blockquote data-path-to-node=3D"12"><p data-path-to-node=3D"12,=
0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Pro Tip:</b> If y=
ou look at <b data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=3D"24">Victron<=
/b> or <b data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=3D"35">Sunny Island=
 (SMA)</b>, you'll find the most robust "Battery Inverters." If you look at=
 <b data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=3D"119">Fronius</b> or <b=
 data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=3D"130">Sungrow</b>, you'll =
mostly find "Hybrids" that <i data-path-to-node=3D"12,0" data-index-in-node=
=3D"173">can</i> be used in AC-coupled mode.</p></blockquote><hr data-path-=
to-node=3D"13"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"14">4. The "Multi-Mode" Inverter</h=
3><p data-path-to-node=3D"15">If you want to be 100% technically accurate a=
t a dinner party, the high-end term is a <b data-path-to-node=3D"15" data-i=
ndex-in-node=3D"86">Multi-Mode Inverter</b>. This describes an inverter tha=
t can operate:</p><ol start=3D"1" data-path-to-node=3D"16"><li><p data-path=
-to-node=3D"16,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"16,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0=
">Grid-Tied:</b> Syncing with the utility.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"16,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"16,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Off-Gr=
id:</b> Creating its own frequency (Grid-Forming).</p></li><li><p data-path=
-to-node=3D"16,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"16,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0=
">Charging:</b> Acting as a rectifier to fill the batteries.</p></li></ol><=
p data-path-to-node=3D"17"><b data-path-to-node=3D"17" data-index-in-node=
=3D"0">Would you like me to compare a dedicated 3-phase Battery Inverter (l=
ike the Victron MultiPlus-II) against a standard Hybrid Inverter to see whi=
ch is more cost-effective for an AC-coupled setup?</b></p></div></message-c=
