p data-path-to-node=3D"0">Using iron or steel for 48V battery busbars is te=
chnically possible but generally discouraged for high-current systems. If y=
ou go this route, you are effectively moving from a "high-performance condu=
ctor" to a "high-resistance heating element."</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"1"=
>Here is the breakdown of why iron is rarely used and what you must do if y=
ou decide to try it.</p><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"2">1. The Conductivity Pro=
blem (The 10% Rule)</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"3">Iron is a poor conductor=
 compared to copper and aluminum.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"4"><li><p dat=
a-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" data-index-in-node=
=3D"0">Conductivity:</b> Iron has roughly <b data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" da=
ta-index-in-node=3D"31">10% to 15%</b> of the conductivity of copper.</p></=
li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0" data-i=
ndex-in-node=3D"0">The Size Penalty:</b> To carry the same current as a sta=
ndard copper busbar without overheating, an iron bar must be <b data-path-t=
o-node=3D"4,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"113">7 to 10 times thicker</b> or wi=
der.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"4,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,2=
,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Voltage Drop:</b> Because iron has higher resi=
stance (<span class=3D"math-inline" data-math=3D"R" data-index-in-node=3D"5=
0"><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><s=
pan class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.6833em;"></span=
><span class=3D"mord mathnormal" style=3D"margin-right: 0.0077em;">R</span>=
</span></span></span></span>), you will lose more energy as heat (<span cla=
ss=3D"math-inline" data-math=3D"P =3D I^2R" data-index-in-node=3D"89"><span=
 class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span clas=
s=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.6833em;"></span><span c=
lass=3D"mord mathnormal" style=3D"margin-right: 0.1389em;">P</span><span cl=
ass=3D"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class=3D"mrel=
">=3D</span><span class=3D"mspace" style=3D"margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span=
></span><span class=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.8141e=
m;"></span><span class=3D"mord"><span class=3D"mord mathnormal" style=3D"ma=
rgin-right: 0.0785em;">I</span><span class=3D"msupsub"><span class=3D"vlist=
-t"><span class=3D"vlist-r"><span class=3D"vlist" style=3D"height: 0.8141em=
;"><span class=3D"" style=3D"top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span cl=
ass=3D"pstrut" style=3D"height: 2.7em;"></span><span class=3D"sizing reset-=
size6 size3 mtight"><span class=3D"mord mtight">2</span></span></span></spa=
n></span></span></span></span><span class=3D"mord mathnormal" style=3D"marg=
in-right: 0.0077em;">R</span></span></span></span></span>). In a 48V system=
, even a 1V drop is significant (it's 2% of your total capacity).</p></li><=
/ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"5">2. Magnetic "Eddy Currents" (The Humming Pr=
oblem)</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"6">Since you are building an AC-coupled =
system, your battery inverter will be pulling and pushing current in cycles=
.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"7"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0">Iron is=
 <b data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"8">ferromagnetic</b>.=
 High currents flowing through iron bars create strong magnetic fields that=
 can cause the bars to physically hum or vibrate at 50/60Hz.</p></li><li><p=
 data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0">This magnetic property can also interfere with=
 nearby sensitive electronics or the Hall-effect sensors used in many Batte=
ry Management Systems (BMS).</p></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"8">3. Ra=
pid Oxidation (Rust)</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"9">Unlike aluminum and cop=
per, which form protective oxide layers, iron forms <b data-path-to-node=3D=
"9" data-index-in-node=3D"75">Iron Oxide (Rust)</b>, which is flaky and non=
-protective.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"10"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"10=
,0,0">Rust is a powerful insulator. If a layer of rust grows between your b=
attery terminal and the bar, the resistance will spike, causing the joint t=
o get hot enough to melt the plastic battery casing.</p></li><li><p data-pa=
th-to-node=3D"10,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D=
"0">The Fix:</b> You would need to <b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-ind=
ex-in-node=3D"27">nickel-plate</b> or <b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-=
index-in-node=3D"43">tin-plate</b> the iron bars to prevent them from becom=
ing a fire hazard over time.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"11"><h3 =
data-path-to-node=3D"12">Comparison: Iron vs. Aluminum vs. Copper</h3><div =
class=3D"horizontal-scroll-wrapper"><div class=3D"table-block-component"><r=
esponse-element class=3D"" ng-version=3D"0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><=
