----><!----><structured-content-container _ngcontent-ng-c2491911150=3D"" cl=
ass=3D"model-response-text processing-state-visible ng-star-inserted" _ngho=
st-ng-c1082903860=3D"" style=3D"height: auto;"><div _ngcontent-ng-c10829038=
60=3D"" class=3D"container"><message-content _ngcontent-ng-c1082903860=3D""=
 _nghost-ng-c1716333038=3D"" id=3D"message-content-id-r_799b15ff0d405692" c=
lass=3D"ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c1716333038=3D"" inline-copy-h=
ost=3D"" class=3D"markdown markdown-main-panel enable-updated-hr-color" id=
=3D"model-response-message-contentr_799b15ff0d405692" aria-live=3D"off" ari=
a-busy=3D"false" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-a=
nimation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0">The short answer is =
<b data-path-to-node=3D"0" data-index-in-node=3D"20">yes</b>, but it is not=
 a "plug-and-play" project. Because Fronius (specifically the <b data-path-=
to-node=3D"0" data-index-in-node=3D"100">Symo GEN24 Plus</b>) uses a propri=
etary communication protocol to talk to its approved batteries (like BYD or=
 LG), you cannot simply wire up a stack of cells and expect it to work.</p>=
<p data-path-to-node=3D"1">However, several advanced DIYers have successful=
ly cracked this nut. Here is how they do it.</p><hr data-path-to-node=3D"2"=
><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"3">1. The "Dala's Emulator" Approach</h3><p data-=
path-to-node=3D"4">The most famous method in the DIY community was pioneere=
d by a developer known as <b data-path-to-node=3D"4" data-index-in-node=3D"=
82">Dala</b>. He created a way to "spoof" the Fronius inverter into thinkin=
g a DIY battery is actually an approved BYD Battery-Box.</p><ul data-path-t=
o-node=3D"5"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,0=
,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">How it works:</b> You use a microcontroller (l=
ike an <b data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"49">ESP32</b> o=
r <b data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"58">Arduino</b>) as =
a bridge. This controller speaks the <b data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-in=
dex-in-node=3D"107">Modbus RTU (RS485)</b> language that Fronius expects.</=
p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" da=
ta-index-in-node=3D"0">The Battery Side:</b> The microcontroller reads the =
actual data (voltage, current, temperature) from a DIY-friendly BMS (like a=
 <b data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"124">Daly</b>, <b dat=
a-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"130">JK</b>, or <b data-path=
-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"137">Batrium</b>).</p></li><li><p =
data-path-to-node=3D"5,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,2,0" data-index-in-no=
de=3D"0">The Translation:</b> It translates that data into the specific CAN=
-bus or Modbus packets that mimic a BYD HVS/HVM system.</p></li></ul><block=
quote data-path-to-node=3D"6"><p data-path-to-node=3D"6,0"><b data-path-to-=
node=3D"6,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Success Story:</b> One notable projec=
t involved taking a <b data-path-to-node=3D"6,0" data-index-in-node=3D"53">=
40kWh Nissan Leaf battery pack</b> (high voltage) and connecting it to a Fr=
onius GEN24 using this emulator logic for a fraction of the cost of a comme=
rcial battery.</p></blockquote><hr data-path-to-node=3D"7"><h3 data-path-to=
-node=3D"8">2. High Voltage Safety (The "Kill Factor")</h3><p data-path-to-=
node=3D"9">Building a 48V battery is like working on a car; building a 400V=
 battery is like working on a regional power substation.</p><ul data-path-t=
o-node=3D"10"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"10,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"1=
0,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Cell Count:</b> To hit the minimum oper=
ating voltage of a Fronius Symo (~150V to 450V), you need roughly <b data-p=
ath-to-node=3D"10,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"105">50 to 140 Lithium Iron Ph=
osphate (LiFePO4) cells</b> in series.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"=
10,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Risk:<=
/b> At 400V DC, electricity doesn't just shock you=E2=80=94it causes your m=
uscles to clamp onto the wire, and it can create "arc flashes" that melt to=
ols.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"10,2,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"10=
,2,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">DIYers use:</b> High-voltage DC contactors, =
specialized HV fuses (TME or Littelfuse), and mid-string disconnects so the=
 pack can be "broken" into safe 48V segments for maintenance.</p></li></ul>=
<hr data-path-to-node=3D"11"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"12">3. The BMS Proble=
m</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"13">Standard "Server Rack" BMS units are desi=
gned for 48V (16 cells). For a Fronius DIY build, you need a <b data-path-t=
o-node=3D"13" data-index-in-node=3D"102">Scalable/Distributed BMS</b>.</p><=
ul data-path-to-node=3D"14"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"14,0,0"><b data-pat=
h-to-node=3D"14,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Batrium:</b> This is the "gol=
d standard" for DIY high voltage. You put a small "LeafMon" or "BlockMon" s=
ensor on every cell, and they all report back to a central WatchMon core.</=
p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"14,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"14,1,0" =
data-index-in-node=3D"0">Orion BMS:</b> Often used in electric vehicle conv=
ersions, this BMS is rugged and specifically designed for strings of up to =
180 cells.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"15"><h3 data-path-to-node=
=3D"16">4. Why most DIYers stick to Victron instead</h3><p data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"17">If your goal is to save money and stay DIY, the Fronius path is th=
e "Hard Mode" version.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"18"><li><p data-path-to-=
node=3D"18,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"18,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">Fr=
onius (DIY HV):</b> High efficiency, sleek look, but requires complex proto=
col hacking and carries a high risk of lethal accident during the build.</p=
></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"18,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"18,1,0" d=
ata-index-in-node=3D"0">Victron (DIY 48V):</b> Completely open-source, nati=
vely supports many DIY BMS units, and works at safe "extra-low" voltages.</=
p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"19"><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"20">Summa=
ry Table for DIY Fronius Battery</h3><div class=3D"horizontal-scroll-wrappe=
r"><div class=3D"table-block-component"><response-element class=3D"" ng-ver=
sion=3D"0.0.0-PLACEHOLDER"><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----><!----=
