d"> Gemini said </h2><!----><!----><structured-content-container _ngcontent=
-ng-c2491911150=3D"" class=3D"model-response-text processing-state-visible =
ng-star-inserted" _nghost-ng-c1082903860=3D"" style=3D"height: auto;"><div =
_ngcontent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" class=3D"container"><message-content _ngcont=
ent-ng-c1082903860=3D"" _nghost-ng-c1716333038=3D"" id=3D"message-content-i=
d-r_04c96ec3edb1a1f3" class=3D"ng-star-inserted"><div _ngcontent-ng-c171633=
3038=3D"" inline-copy-host=3D"" class=3D"markdown markdown-main-panel enabl=
e-updated-hr-color" id=3D"model-response-message-contentr_04c96ec3edb1a1f3"=
 aria-live=3D"off" aria-busy=3D"false" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-dur=
ation: 400ms; --fade-animation-function: linear;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0=
">It is absolutely possible, but "possible" and "simple" are two different =
things when you move from a one-way inverter to a <b data-path-to-node=3D"0=
" data-index-in-node=3D"123">bidirectional inverter/charger</b>.</p><p data=
-path-to-node=3D"1">In the DIY world, this is known as the <b data-path-to-=
node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"39">"Holy Grail"</b> of power electronics =
because the device must be able to switch its role: it must be a <b data-pa=
th-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"138">Rectifier</b> (AC to DC) to cha=
rge the battery and an <b data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"188=
">Inverter</b> (DC to AC) to power your house, often using the same heavy-d=
uty magnetic components.</p><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"2">1. The DIY Hardware=
 Path</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"3">To build a 48V bidirectional unit, you=
 generally need a <b data-path-to-node=3D"3" data-index-in-node=3D"56">H-Br=
idge</b> on the AC side and a <b data-path-to-node=3D"3" data-index-in-node=
=3D"86">Buck-Boost stage</b> or a <b data-path-to-node=3D"3" data-index-in-=
node=3D"108">Dual Active Bridge (DAB)</b> on the DC side.</p><ul data-path-=
to-node=3D"4"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,=
0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">OwnTech OwnVerter:</b> As we discussed, this =
is a <b data-path-to-node=3D"4,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"46">native bidire=
ctional</b> platform. Its hardware (the "Twist" and "Spin" boards) is desig=
ned to move power in both directions. You can program it to act as a batter=
y charger by simply reversing the control logic in the firmware.</p></li><l=
i><p data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0" data-index-=
in-node=3D"0">STMicroelectronics Reference Design:</b> If you are comfortab=
le with the <b data-path-to-node=3D"4,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"69">STM32G=
474</b> (the C2000's biggest rival), ST offers a complete 6.6kW Bidirection=
al AC/DC solution including schematics and firmware. It targets a 98% peak =
efficiency.</p></li></ul><hr data-path-to-node=3D"5"><h3 data-path-to-node=
=3D"6">2. The Core Engineering Challenges</h3><p data-path-to-node=3D"7">To=
